   <mods:abstract>Captain Stanhope's letter to Governor Bowdoin disregarded his
            recommendation to seek redress from insults through the laws of the state of
            Massachusetts and was highly disrespectful. Respect for government based on the
            rectitude of its position and it should never be ill-treated with impunity. Such conduct
            tends to alienate the good will of the other. The papers should be sent to the British
            Minister with the statement that only a desire to maintain good will prevents a protest
            being made. Sure Britain will be as displeased as Congress by the correspondence. Sure
            Britain will consider this instance of moderation in its true light.
            (enclosures)</mods:abstract>
